</div><div class="jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOutput " data-mime-type="text/markdown">
<h3 id="PACF-Informed-AIC/BIC-Selection-Over-Train-Ratios">PACF-Informed AIC/BIC Selection Over Train Ratios<a class="anchor-link" href="#PACF-Informed-AIC/BIC-Selection-Over-Train-Ratios">&#182;</a></h3><p>The train ratio and lag order are coupled. If the training window changes, the PACF changes, the residual variance changes, and the AIC/BIC-optimal lag order may change.</p>
<p>Therefore, for each candidate training ratio (r), we:</p>
<ol>
<li>Split the series into train/test using (r).</li>
<li>Compute PACF on the training set.</li>
<li>Use significant PACF lags to define a candidate maximum lag.</li>
<li>Fit AR$(p)$ models for $p = 1,\dots,p_{\max}^{PACF}$.</li>
<li>Compute AIC and BIC on the training set.</li>
<li>For each train ratio, choose the BIC-best lag.</li>
<li>Among those BIC-selected models, choose the train-ratio/lag-order pair with the best one-step test $R^2$.</li>
</ol>
<p>This makes the test set act as a validation set, so the resulting $R^2$ should be interpreted as validation performance rather than an untouched final test estimate.</p>

</div>
