<h2 id="2---Inference">2 - Inference<a class="anchor-link" href="#2---Inference">&#182;</a></h2><p>Let $\hat{x}$ be assumed to follow the $AR(p)$ model with mean intercept. Recall that at each time $t &gt; p$, 
$$ x_t = a_0 + a_1 x_{t-1} + \dots + a_p x_{t-p} + c + \epsilon_t \\ =  a_0 + x_{t-1:t-p}a + \epsilon_t$$
where $$a_0: \text{mean-intercept constant}, \\ a = [a_0 \ a_1 \ a_2 \ \dots \ a_p]^T: \text{model coefficients}, \\ x_{t-1:t-p} = [x_{t-1} \ x_{t-2} \ \dots \ x_{t-p}]^T: \text{$p$ timepoints to the past from timepoint $t$}, \\ \epsilon_t : \text{ zero-mean, constant-variance, uncorrelated noise observations}.$$</p>
<p>Consider all model-able timepoints. Thus, ignore the first $p$ timepoints). Thus,</p>
$$x = [x_{p+1} \ x_{p+2} \ \dots \ x_{n}]^T.$$<p>Then, write the time series based on the autoregressive model as follows:
$$x = \begin{bmatrix} x_p \\ x_{p+1} \\ \vdots \\ x_n \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} &amp; 1 \ x_p \ x_{p-1} \ \dots \ x_1 \\ &amp;1 \ x_{p+1} \ x_{p} \ \dots \ x_{2} \\ &amp;\vdots \ \vdots \ \dots \ \vdots \\ &amp; 1 \ x_{n-1} \ x_{n-2} \ \dots \ x_{n-1-p} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} a_0 \\ a_1 \\ a_2 \\ \vdots \\ a_p\end{bmatrix} + \begin{bmatrix} \epsilon_p \\ \epsilon_{p+1} \\ \vdots \\ \epsilon_{n} \end{bmatrix} \\ =  \begin{bmatrix} 1 \  x_{p:1}^T \\ 1 \ x_{p+1:2}^T \\ \vdots \\ 1 \ x_{n-1:n-1-p}^T \end{bmatrix} a + \epsilon \\ = X a + \epsilon.$$</p>
<p>Estimate the time series by estimating the optimal coefficients as minimizers of the least-squares error objective:</p>
$$
\hat{a} := \arg\min_a \|x - Xa\|_2^2, \qquad \hat{x} := X\hat{a}.
$$<p>The least-squares objective is
$$
\|x - Xa\|_2^2 = (x - Xa)^T(x - Xa).
$$</p>
<p>The optimal coefficients $\hat{a}$ occur when the first-order derivative is zero:
$$
0 = \frac{\partial}{\partial a} (x - Xa)^T(x - Xa)\bigg|_{a=\hat{a}}
= -2X^T(x - X\hat{a})
$$</p>
<p>Equivalently:
$$
X^T X \hat{a} = X^T x
$$</p>
<p>If $X^T X$ is invertible, then
$$
\boxed{\hat{a} = (X^T X)^{-1}X^T x}
$$</p>

