<h2 id="Testing-Stationarity">Testing Stationarity<a class="anchor-link" href="#Testing-Stationarity">&#182;</a></h2><h3 id="5.1---Stationarity-Robustness-via-Bootstrap">5.1 - Stationarity Robustness via Bootstrap<a class="anchor-link" href="#5.1---Stationarity-Robustness-via-Bootstrap">&#182;</a></h3><p>Since the coefficients are estimated from data, it is not enough to check stationarity only for the point estimate $\hat{a}$. To assess robustness, we bootstrap the coefficient estimates and test whether the resulting characteristic polynomials remain stationary.</p>
<p>Using the asymptotic normal approximation,
$$
\hat{a} \approx \mathcal{N}\left(a,\hat{\sigma}^2 (X^T X)^{-1}\right),
$$
we generate bootstrap samples
$$
a^{(1)},a^{(2)},\dots,a^{(B)} \sim \mathcal{N}\left(\hat{a},\hat{\sigma}^2 (X^T X)^{-1}\right).
$$</p>
<p>For each bootstrap sample $a^{(b)} = (a_1^{(b)},\dots,a_p^{(b)})$, define the corresponding characteristic polynomial
$$
\phi^{(b)}(z) = 1-a_1^{(b)} z-a_2^{(b)} z^2-\dots-a_p^{(b)} z^p.
$$</p>
<p>Then test whether all roots of $\phi^{(b)}(z)$ lie outside the unit circle:
$$
\forall z,\ (\phi^{(b)}(z)=0 \implies |z|&gt;1).
$$</p>
<p>Define the stationarity indicator
$$
I^{(b)} =
\begin{cases}
1, &amp; \text{if all roots of } \phi^{(b)}(z) \text{ satisfy } |z|&gt;1,\\
0, &amp; \text{otherwise.}
\end{cases}
$$</p>
<p>The bootstrap stationarity score is then
$$
\hat{p}_{\mathrm{stat}} = \frac{1}{B}\sum_{b=1}^B I^{(b)}.
$$</p>
<p>This quantity estimates the proportion of plausible coefficient vectors, under the sampling uncertainty of $\hat{a}$, that produce a stationary $AR(p)$ process.</p>
<h3 id="5.2---Interpretation">5.2 - Interpretation<a class="anchor-link" href="#5.2---Interpretation">&#182;</a></h3><ul>
<li>If $\hat{p}_{\mathrm{stat}} \approx 1$, then stationarity is robust.</li>
<li>If $\hat{p}_{\mathrm{stat}}$ is close to $0$, then the fitted model is not robustly stationary.</li>
<li>Intermediate values indicate that the estimated process lies near the boundary of stationarity.</li>
</ul>
<p>Thus, the bootstrap procedure gives a practical measure of how sensitive the stationarity conclusion is to estimation uncertainty.</p>
<h3 id="5.3---Decision-Rule-via-Significance-Level">5.3 - Decision Rule via Significance Level<a class="anchor-link" href="#5.3---Decision-Rule-via-Significance-Level">&#182;</a></h3><p>Let $\hat{p}_{\mathrm{stat}}$ denote the bootstrap estimate of the probability that the process is stationary.</p>
<p>Fix a significance level $\alpha \in (0,1)$.</p>
<p>We reject stationarity if
$$
\hat{p}_{\mathrm{stat}} &lt; 1 - \alpha,
$$
i.e. if the probability of non-stationarity exceeds $\alpha$.</p>
<p>Equivalently, we accept stationarity only if the estimated parameter uncertainty places at least $(1-\alpha)$ mass inside the stationary region.</p>

